Harry Potter's Literary Magic
PRINCETON — This summer, readers around the world celebrated the 20th anniversary of the first edition of J.K. Rowling's Harry Potter series — Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone (known as Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone in the U.S.) at literary festivals and bookstores. They had ample reason to do so.
Since the young wizard made his debut on June 26, 1997, this "boy who lived" has become a symbol of "tenacity and endurance."
In the past 20 years, the Harry Potter series has expanded to include seven novels, translated into 70 languages, and sold over 450 million copies combined.
The eight films based on the books have grossed $7 billion, while Harry Potter-themed toys and merchandise have generated another $7 billion in revenue.
<s>For a certain age and mindset, it is hard to imagine a day when global audiences were not enchanted by Rowling's works.
<s>Therefore, I was astonished to recall my students' terrible reaction to Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone in the fall of 1999, when I had included it in the syllabus for my course in popular literature at Princeton University. I had been teaching a series of courses on best-sellers from the 17th century to the present for over six years.
<s>The course explores popular works from these periods and invites students to ponder why and how such best-sellers attract their audiences.
<s>At the end of each semester, I would ask students to choose one last work representing the popular taste of the time.
<s>In 1999, they chose the first Harry Potter novel.
<s>That year, the Harry Potter fever hit the American shore with full force.
<s>In June, the U.S. publishers of the series rushed to push the hardcover edition of Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets onto bookstore shelves.
<s>The same institution also published the third installment, Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban, and the paperback version of Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone in September 8.
<s>By the end of the month, J.K. Rowling's novels had dominated the New York Times Best Sellers list, with the paperback version of Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone topping the paperback sales chart.
<s>Time magazine even featured the bespectacled wizard on its cover.
<s>Harry Potter's image can be seen everywhere you look.
<s>My students couldn't wait to find out why such enthusiasm existed.
<s>Oh my god, they were completely disappointed.
<s>In their eyes, the Harry Potter series was nothing but second-rate nonsense, far beneath works like The Chronicles of Narnia or The Lord of the Rings that they treasured from their childhood.
<s>Although their childhood had only passed a few years ago, they criticized the Harry Potter series like notorious adult critics, saying it was "made up," "poorly written," "clichéd," and "boring."

In their view, Harry had none of the wonder, wit, or warmth.
Their distaste surprised me, but in retrospect, it was hardly cause for alarm.
While adults have always constituted a large part of the Harry Potter audience, these students were precisely in the wrong age bracket to appreciate the phenomenon objectively.
They were too old to accept new children's literature but still lacked the perspective of parents (I, for my part, had just become a parent at the time), eagerly insisting that despite the series' current popularity, it would soon be forgotten.
<s>Second year autumn, that is, 2000, the next batch of students also chose Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone as their final analysis book, just like their predecessors, they confidently rejected this work.
<s>Fast forward to spring 2007.
<s>After postponing the course for several years, I once again taught 'American Bestsellers.'
<s>When students chose their final analysis book, they selected Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone.
<s>And I was prepared to face their criticism.
But this time, their comments were very positive.
This was a new generation of students, born between 1986 and 1989, who first read Rowling's works not as college students but as teenagers just entering adolescence. This means they grew up alongside Harry, Ron, and Hermione.
The same thing happened in the fall of 2010.
To them, "We grew up with Harry Potter" is a motto, not a label.
Will Harry eventually fade from memory?
As long as we are alive, it is impossible.
I taught a course on bestsellers twice since 2010, and both times the students chose non-Harry Potter novels for their final review.
Are they tired of Harry Potter?
Given the comments on the Harry Potter series in my other course on children's literature, it is unlikely.
Now, I am choosing to include a Harry Potter novel in the syllabus, but I did not choose Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone; instead, I chose Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban – which is my favorite in the seven-book series and marks the transition from children's literature to young adult fiction, with complex portrayals of loyalty, betrayal, anger, and compassion.
My many students also love this book the most.
But how long will the popularity of the Harry Potter series last?
Each time I teach a course on children's literature, I conduct a poll : "Which books on the syllabus did you read during your childhood?"
In 2010, 86% had read Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban.
In 2012, this number rose to 94%.
But the percentages continued to decline in subsequent years — 87% in 2014, and down to 81% in 2016.
I know these are not scientific figures.
But I am curious: Will the percentage of students who have read Harry Potter drop below 80% when I teach 'Children's Literature' again in the spring of next year?
Will the fact prove the students of 1999 and 2000 correct, that Harry Potter's status is declining and it will never become a classic work?
Or is there a balance point where the percentage stabilizes and no longer declines?
<s>Perhaps Harry's 40th anniversary will tell us the answer.
<s>Until then, I am happy to continue inviting him into my classroom.
